Lampiao

Target IP: 192.168.186.48

Scanning

There are three TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH, HTTP, and another HTTP. I will start enumeration with the two HTTP applications on the higher ports on the target machine.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The HTTP application on port displays the webpage above. The source-code of the page does not provide any hints either.

Port 1898: HTTP

This port contains another HTTP application built using Drupal.


Running a whatweb scan against this port outputs the result above. The target host seems to be running Drupal 7. Before performing a directory search, I wish to enumerate this application further.



The first article contains the name of an mp3 file. The author, Eder, also mentions Node 2 is not working :(. However, browsing to http://192.168.186.48:1898/LuizGonzaga-LampiaoFalou.mp3, I was able to access the mp3 file.


Browsing to http://192.168.186.48:1898/?q=node/2 reveals node 2. This article contains two more files: audio.m4a and qrc.png.


Browsing to http://192.168.186.48:1898/audio.m4a contains an audio clip mentioning user tiago. Now we have a possible usernme.



And lastly, a QR code is displayed on page http://192.168.186.48:1898/qrc.png. Decoding this QR code gives the output above.



Performing a Drupal scan shows an important information: the version! The version of the application is 7.54, meaning it is vulnerable to Drupalgeddon2 RCE.

Exploitation

First Method

I used Metasploit Framework to exploit this vulnerable machine. I used the exploit unix/webapp/drupal_drupalgeddon2. I also set the options for the exploit, as shown above. I used the default payload for this exploit.


And now I have a foothold on the machine as www-data using this exploit.

Second Method
After completing this challenge. I noticed there is another way of exploiting the machine. That is by using cewl to generate the possible passwords from the second article. And then fuzzing the login page with the username and the passwords from the article. This is because the password Virgulino appears in the article.

Privilege Escalation


After some enumeration, I found the Drupal's username and password located at /var/www/html/sites/default/settings.php


And spraying that password against tiago worked. Now I have access to tiago's account.



Looks like the target machine is vulnerable to a kernel exploit. After trying a few different kernel exploits, I notice the exploit above only works against this target machine.


After transferring the exploit 40847 to the target machine, I followed the commands for the exploit to gain a root shell.

Flags


The local.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine.


The proof.txt flag once I used the kernel exploit to gain a root shell.
